5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6
7 PART I. DIGITAL ASSET FINANCIAL ACT
8 SECTION 1.(a) Chapter 53 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
9 Article to read:
10 "Article 26.
11 "Digital Asset Financial Act.
12 "§ 53-441. Definitions.
13 The following definitions apply in this Article:
14 (1) Customer. – A person for which a financial institution provides digital asset
15 services, including a digital asset account holder or a person on whose behalf
16 the financial institution acts in a fiduciary capacity.
17 (2) Digital asset. – A natively electronic asset that confers economic, proprietary,
18 or access rights and is recorded or stored in a blockchain, cryptographically
19 secured distributed ledger, or similar technology. A digital asset is personal
20 property.
21 (3) Digital asset custody services. – The safekeeping or custody of digital assets
22 on behalf of customers by a financial institution, including maintaining control
23 over the digital assets and any associated cryptographic keys.
24 (4) Digital asset services. – Any services involving digital assets offered by a
25 financial institution, including digital asset custody services, staking services,
26 and digital asset transaction services.
27 (5) Digital asset transaction services. – Services that facilitate the execution of
28 digital asset purchase or sale transactions on behalf of a customer.
29 (6) Exercise of an act of ownership interest. – Includes the following actions by a
30 customer relating to a digital asset account:
31 a. Conducting a transaction with digital assets in the account, including
32 buying or selling digital assets.
*H1029-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 b. Depositing into or withdrawing from a digital asset account fiat
2 currency or other property, whether by a one-time transaction or a
3 recurring transaction.
4 c. Electronically accessing the digital asset account.
5 d. Conducting any activity with respect to another digital asset account
6 or any other property held with the same financial institution.
7 e. Taking any other action that reasonably demonstrates to the financial
8 institution that the customer knows that the digital asset account exists.
9 (7) Fiduciary capacity. – Acting with trust powers under State law to provide
10 digital asset services on behalf of a customer, including the discretionary
11 management or administration of digital assets subject to fiduciary duties.
12 (8) Financial institution. – A bank chartered under State law or a credit union
13 organized under State law.
14 (9) Keys. – A pair of cryptographic codes associated with a digital asset wallet,
15 consisting of a public key and a private key. The public key enables the receipt
16 of digital assets and the verification of digital signatures. The private key
17 enables the control, transfer, or management of digital assets within the wallet.
18 (10) Non-fiduciary capacity. – Providing digital asset custody services solely for
19 safekeeping, without discretionary authority to manage or transfer the assets
20 and with legal title and control of the assets remaining with the customer.
21 (11) Regulating authority. – Either of the following:
22 a. In the case of a State-chartered bank, the Commissioner of Banks.
23 b. In the case of a State-organized credit union, the Administrator of
24 Credit Unions.
25 (12) Slashing. – A penalty imposed by a blockchain protocol that results in the
26 forfeiture or reduction of staked digital assets or rewards due to validator
27 misconduct or failure.
28 (13) Staking. – Committing digital assets to a blockchain network to participate in
29 the network's operations by validating transactions, proposing and attesting to
30 blocks, and securing the network.
31 (14) Staking rewards. – Any interest, yield, or other compensation earned by a
32 customer through staking digital assets on a blockchain network.
33 (15) Subcustodian. – A third party that a financial institution uses to hold digital
34 assets on the financial institution's behalf as part of providing custody services
35 to a customer.
36 (16) Wallet. – A digital interface or physical device that stores digital assets or
37 private keys, enabling the owner to securely manage, transfer, and maintain
38 independent control over their digital assets.
39 "§ 53-442. Digital asset custody services.
40 (a) Notification. – A financial institution intending to offer digital asset custody services
41 shall notify the regulating authority in writing before initiating these services. The written notice
42 shall be provided to the regulating authority at least 60 days before the financial institution's
43 commencement of custody services and shall include any information required by the regulating
44 authority to evaluate the financial institution's plans, policies, and procedures for compliance
45 with this section.
46 (b) Fiduciary Capacity. – A financial institution shall not begin offering digital asset
47 custody services in a fiduciary capacity without first obtaining the written approval of the
48 regulating authority. In applying for approval, the financial institution shall demonstrate that it
49 has satisfied all requirements to exercise trust powers and that it has the necessary expertise,
50 policies, and procedures in place to safely conduct fiduciary digital asset custody services. The
51 regulating authority has the discretion to condition or limit the scope of a financial institution's
Page 2 House Bill 1029-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 authority to engage in fiduciary digital asset custody services and may impose any supervisory
2 conditions deemed necessary to ensure the safety and soundness of the financial institution and
3 the protection of customer assets. Additionally, if a financial institution provides digital asset
4 custody services in a fiduciary capacity and uses a subcustodian for those assets, the financial
5 institution shall provide notice to the regulating authority of its use of a subcustodian for fiduciary
6 custody.
7 (c) Fiduciary and Non-Fiduciary Capacity. – A financial institution may directly provide
8 digital asset custody services to its customers and may provide digital asset custody services in
9 either a fiduciary capacity or a non-fiduciary capacity, subject to the following provisions:
10 (1) Fiduciary capacity. – A financial institution shall not provide digital asset
11 custody services in a fiduciary capacity unless it is authorized to exercise trust
12 powers under State law. A financial institution acting in a fiduciary capacity
13 shall exercise this authority in accordance with all applicable fiduciary duties
14 and standards, including those governing trustees, custodians, and agents
15 under State law.
16 (2) Non-fiduciary capacity. – A financial institution may provide digital asset
17 custody services in a non-fiduciary capacity without being authorized to
18 exercise trust powers. When acting in a non-fiduciary capacity, the financial
19 institution shall act solely as a custodian for safekeeping purposes and shall
20 not exercise discretionary authority over the customer's digital assets. The
21 financial institution may act only upon the written instructions of the customer
22 and shall not independently manage, transfer, or dispose of the digital assets.
23 (d) Customer Agreement and Disclosures. – A financial institution shall enter into a
24 written custodial agreement with each customer before undertaking digital asset custody services.
25 The custodial agreement shall specify whether the financial institution is acting in a fiduciary
26 capacity or a non-fiduciary capacity for that customer. The agreement shall also include the
27 following written disclosures in a clear and conspicuous manner:
28 (1) Digital assets held in custody by the financial institution are not deposits,
29 obligations, or other liabilities of the institution.
30 (2) Digital assets in custody are not insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance
31 Corporation (FDIC), the National Credit Union Administration (NCUA), or
32 any other federal or State deposit insurance or share insurance program.
33 (e) Pooled or Segregated Custody Permitted. – A financial institution may hold digital
34 assets of multiple customers in a pooled custody arrangement or may segregate digital assets by
35 individual customer, in accordance with its custodial agreements. Pooled custody is permitted so
36 long as the financial institution maintains accurate records identifying each customer's interest in
37 the digital assets. A financial institution may segregate a customer's digital assets in a separate
38 account or digital wallet upon a customer's request or as required by the custodial agreement or
39 other law.
40 (f) Asset Reserve Requirement. – A financial institution providing digital asset custody
41 services shall at all times maintain control over a quantity of each type of digital asset in its
42 custody that equals or exceeds the total quantity of that digital asset owed to customers or
43 required to be held on behalf of customers. In no event shall the financial institution hold less
44 than a one hundred percent (100%) reserve of each digital asset owed or attributable to its
45 customers, and the financial institution's aggregate holdings of each digital asset shall at all times
46 be equal to or greater than the total amount of that asset that the financial institution owes to its
47 customers. Pooled custody of assets, as provided in subsection (e) of this section, shall not relieve
48 the financial institution of the requirement to individually account for and fully reserve each type
49 of digital asset for the benefit of customers under this subsection.
50 (g) Independent Annual Audits. – A financial institution engaging in digital asset custody
51 services shall undergo an independent audit of its custodial activities and holdings at least once
House Bill 1029-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 every fiscal year. The audit shall be conducted by a qualified independent auditor and shall verify
2 that the financial institution's actual holdings of each digital asset exceed the amount of that
3 digital asset that the institution owes to or holds for customers. The financial institution shall
4 promptly provide the results of each annual audit to the regulating authority and shall make the
5 audit results available to its customers upon request.
6 "§ 53-443. Subcustody of digital assets.
7 (a) A financial institution may utilize one or more subcustodians to assist in providing
8 digital asset custody services to its customers. The engagement of a subcustodian does not require
9 a separate consent from the customer, so long as the use of subcustodians is disclosed in the
10 customer's custodial agreement. The use of a subcustodian does not relieve the financial
11 institution of its duties as custodian, and the financial institution remains responsible to the
12 customer for the custody of the digital assets.
13 (b) A financial institution may place digital assets into subcustody only with one of the
14 following entities:
15 (1) A bank chartered under the laws of this State, another state, or the United
16 States.
17 (2) A special purpose depository institution chartered under the laws of another
18 state.
19 (3) A money transmitter licensed under Article 16B of this Chapter.
20 (c) A financial institution shall execute a written agreement with each subcustodian it
21 uses. Each agreement shall delineate the rights and responsibilities of the financial institution and
22 the subcustodian and require compliance with this section. The financial institution shall make a
23 subcustodial agreement available to the regulating authority for review upon request.
24 (d) A financial institution placing digital assets in subcustody shall at all times retain
25 control and custody of those assets. The subcustodial arrangement shall be structured so that the
26 financial institution remains the custodial recordholder of the assets on behalf of its customers
27 and the digital assets remain the property of the financial institution's customers.
28 (e) For each digital asset held in subcustody, the financial institution shall require the
29 subcustodian to maintain at least a one hundred percent (100%) reserve of that asset by type. The
30 amount of each type of digital asset held by the subcustodian shall at all times equal or exceed
31 the amount of that asset credited to the financial institution's customers. Different types of digital
32 assets shall not be commingled for reserve purposes, and assets held by a subcustodian on behalf
33 of one financial institution shall not be commingled with assets held on behalf of any other
34 financial institution or person.
35 (f) A financial institution shall only utilize a subcustodian that maintains insurance
36 coverage sufficient to protect against the loss of digital assets due to cybersecurity breaches, theft,
37 or other similar events. The financial institution shall ensure that the subcustodian's insurance
38 remains in effect and adequate to cover the value of assets held in subcustody.
39 (g) Digital assets held in subcustody shall be included in the scope of the financial
40 institution's annual independent audits under G.S. 53-442(g). All records relating to digital assets
41 held in subcustody are subject to examination by the regulating authority to the same extent as
42 records relating to digital assets held directly by the financial institution.
43 "§ 53-444. Staking of digital assets.
44 (a) Regulatory Notification and Approval. – A financial institution shall notify the
45 regulating authority in writing of its intent to offer staking services at least 60 days before
46 initiating these services. The written notice shall include any information that the regulating
47 authority requires to evaluate the financial institution's plans, policies, and procedures for
48 conducting staking in a safe and sound manner. A financial institution shall not begin staking
49 digital assets in a fiduciary capacity on behalf of a customer without first obtaining the written
50 approval of the regulating authority.
Page 4 House Bill 1029-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) Staking Services. – A financial institution may stake digital assets held in custody on
2 behalf of its customers. Staking services may be provided with respect to digital assets held in
3 either a fiduciary capacity or non-fiduciary capacity, subject to the requirements of this section.
4 Unless otherwise instructed by the customer, a financial institution may include a customer's
5 digital assets in its staking program by default, so long as the customer has been given the
6 required disclosures and an opportunity to opt out as described in subsection (c) of this section.
7 (c) Customer Disclosures and Opt-Out. – Before initiating staking services for any
8 customer's digital assets, a financial institution shall provide the customer with a clear and
9 conspicuous written disclosure of the terms and conditions of the staking program, including the
10 following:
11 (1) Automatic staking and opt-out. – That the financial institution may
12 automatically stake digital assets in the customer's account unless the
13 customer affirmatively opts out of participation.
14 (2) Risks of staking. – The key risks associated with staking, such as the potential
15 for loss of staked assets or rewards due to slashing or other network events,
16 and cybersecurity or operational risks inherent in the staking process.
17 (3) Lock-up periods. – Any applicable lock-up, unbonding, or notice period
18 before staked assets can be withdrawn or transferred and the implications of
19 this period for the customer's access to the customer's assets.
20 (4) Customer rights. – The customer's rights and obligations related to the staking
21 service, including the right to discontinue participation in staking at any time
22 and the entitlement to receive staking rewards earned on the customer's assets.
23 (5) Fees. – The amount or rate of any fees or commissions that the financial
24 institution deducts from staking rewards as compensation for providing the
25 staking service.
26 (d) Customer Ownership and Off-Balance Sheet Status. – A digital asset that a financial
27 institution stakes on behalf of a customer remains the property of the customer. Staked customer
28 assets, and any staking rewards associated with those assets, shall not be recorded as assets or
29 liabilities on the financial institution's balance sheet. The financial institution shall ensure that
30 staked assets are safeguarded and not subject to any lien, security interest, or claim of the
31 financial institution's creditors. A financial institution shall not encumber, hypothecate, or
32 otherwise use a customer's staked assets for any purpose except for facilitating staking on the
33 relevant blockchain or distributed ledger and shall not expose the assets to risk of loss except to
34 the extent inherent in the normal operation of the staking process.
35 (e) Use of Subcustodians for Staking. – A financial institution may utilize one or more
36 subcustodians to facilitate the staking of digital assets on behalf of its customers. The financial
37 institution shall at all times retain control over the staked assets and maintain appropriate
38 oversight of the staking process. The use of a subcustodian for staking does not relieve the
39 financial institution of its duties to the customer under this section, and the financial institution
40 remains responsible for ensuring compliance with all requirements of this section. A subcustodial
41 arrangement for staking shall be executed in a written agreement that delineates the rights and
42 responsibilities of the financial institution and the subcustodian.
43 (f) Reserve Requirements for Staked Assets. – In addition to complying with the reserve
44 requirements of this Article, a financial institution shall ensure that a sufficient portion of each
45 digital asset type remains unstaked or otherwise available to promptly meet customer withdrawal
46 requests, subject to any staking lock-up or unbonding periods disclosed to the customer pursuant
47 to subsection (c) of this section.
48 (g) Staking Rewards to Customers. – All rewards, yield, or other benefits earned from
49 the staking of a customer's digital assets shall accrue to the benefit of that customer. A financial
50 institution may deduct a reasonable fee or commission from staking rewards only if that fee has
51 been disclosed to the customer in advance in writing. Except as otherwise agreed in writing by
House Bill 1029-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 the customer, the financial institution shall credit all net staking rewards, after the deduction of
2 any disclosed fees, to the customer's account in the same type of digital asset that generated the
3 rewards. These credits shall be made within a reasonable period after the rewards are received or
4 become available to the financial institution.
5 (h) Audits, Risk Management, and Insurance. – A financial institution's staking activities
6 shall be included within the scope of its independent annual audits under G.S. 53-442(g). The
7 financial institution shall implement and maintain written internal policies and procedures to
8 effectively identify, monitor, and manage risks associated with staking, including operational
9 risks, cybersecurity threats, slashing, and other risks associated with staking services. The
10 financial institution shall maintain insurance coverage adequate to protect against potential losses
11 arising from staking activities, including losses attributable to slashing, cybersecurity breaches,
12 theft, or similar events, and shall ensure this coverage remains in effect and sufficient to cover
13 the current value of assets staked on behalf of its customers. All records relating to the financial
14 institution's staking services shall be available for independent audit and examination by the
15 regulating authority, consistent with the treatment of non-staked custodial asset records.
16 "§ 53-445. Digital asset transaction services.
17 (a) Regulatory Notice. – A financial institution intending to engage in digital asset
18 transaction services under this section shall provide at least 60 days' written notice of its intent
19 to the regulating authority. The financial institution may commence these services only after the
20 notice period has elapsed unless the regulating authority allows an earlier date.
21 (b) Fiduciary Capacity. – A financial institution may engage in digital asset transaction
22 services when acting in a fiduciary capacity on behalf of a customer, subject to the requirements
23 of this section.
24 (c) Customer Disclosures. – A financial institution shall disclose to its customer, before
25 or at the time of a digital asset transaction, the following disclosures in a clear and conspicuous
26 manner:
27 (1) The methodology or basis used to determine the execution price of the digital
28 asset transaction.
29 (2) Any spreads, fees, commissions, or other charges that will be applied to the
30 transaction.
31 (3) The expected time line for settlement of the transaction and for the digital
32 asset to be available in the customer's account.
33 (d) Customer Instruction or Discretionary Authority. – A financial institution shall
34 execute a digital asset transaction only if one or more of the following applies:
35 (1) The transaction is executed pursuant to the express instruction of the
36 customer.
37 (2) The transaction is executed in the exercise of discretionary investment
38 authority granted to the financial institution under the governing fiduciary
39 instrument or other law.
40 (e) Counterparties. – A financial institution shall facilitate digital asset transactions only
41 with counterparties who are also authorized to engage in digital asset transaction services.
42 (f) Prohibition on Proprietary Trading. – A financial institution engaging in digital asset
43 transaction services under this section shall act solely in a fiduciary capacity for the benefit of its
44 customers and shall not engage in proprietary trading of digital assets. No purchase or sale of a
45 digital asset shall be made for the financial institution's own account under the authority of this
46 section, and all transactions shall be solely for the account of, or benefit of, a customer.
47 (g) Use of Subcustodians and Execution Agents. – A financial institution engaging in
48 digital asset transaction services under this section may utilize subcustodians or third-party
49 execution agents to execute transactions on behalf of its customers. The financial institution may
50 delegate discretionary authority to these subcustodians or agents regarding the timing, sequence,
51 and venue of transaction execution. This delegation shall comply with the fiduciary
Page 6 House Bill 1029-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 responsibilities of the financial institution. The financial institution shall perform due diligence
2 and maintain continuous monitoring of every subcustodian or execution agent to ensure
3 compliance with this Article and the protection of digital assets. Delegation of authority under
4 this subsection does not relieve the financial institution of its fiduciary obligations or its
5 responsibility to comply with this Article.
6 (h) Custody of Assets Post-Transaction. – A financial institution that purchases a digital
7 asset under this section shall ensure that the asset is transferred into the financial institution's
8 custody as soon as commercially practicable after execution of the transaction. All digital assets
9 so acquired shall be held in custody in accordance with the fiduciary custody standards
10 established in this Article and maintained under the financial institution's control consistent with
11 its fiduciary obligations.
12 (i) Record Keeping and Oversight. – For each digital asset purchase or sale executed
13 under this section, the financial institution shall create and retain a record of the transaction,
14 including the date and time of execution; the type and amount of digital asset purchased or sold;
15 the price at which the transaction was executed; the identity of the counterparty; any execution
16 agent used; and all fees, commissions, or spreads charged. These records shall be maintained for
17 at least five years and shall be made available to the regulating authority upon request or during
18 examination.
19 "§ 53-446. Anti-money laundering, cybersecurity, and other compliance requirements.
20 (a) Compliance. – A financial institution shall comply with all federal and State laws
21 governing its digital asset services. These laws include the federal Bank Secrecy Act (31 U.S.C.
22 § 5311 et seq.) and its implementing regulations, customer due diligence requirements issued by
23 the U.S. Department of the Treasury's Financial Crimes Enforcement Network, sanctions
24 regulations administered by the U.S. Department of the Treasury's Office of Foreign Assets
25 Control (OFAC), and data security and privacy laws, such as the Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act (15
26 U.S.C. § 6801 et seq.) and its implementing regulations.
27 (b) Anti-Money Laundering Program. – A financial institution shall establish and
28 maintain an anti-money laundering compliance program that is risk-based and commensurate
29 with the nature and scope of the financial institution's digital asset services. The program shall
30 include all of the following:
31 (1) A system of internal controls to ensure ongoing compliance with the Bank
32 Secrecy Act and other applicable anti-money laundering requirements.
33 (2) Independent testing for compliance to be conducted by qualified internal audit
34 personnel or an independent party.
35 (3) Appropriate risk-based procedures for conducting ongoing customer due
36 diligence, including monitoring of customer transactions and updating
37 customer information as necessary.
38 (c) Cybersecurity Program. – A financial institution shall implement and maintain a
39 written cybersecurity program designed to ensure the security of the financial institution's digital
40 asset services systems and protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of customer
41 digital assets and related information. The cybersecurity program shall be commensurate with
42 the financial institution's size and complexity and the sensitivity of its operations and shall align
43 with federal cybersecurity standards for institutions, including the guidelines of the Federal
44 Financial Institutions Examination Council (FFIEC) Information Technology Examination
45 Handbook and the framework established by the National Institute of Standards and Technology
46 (NIST). The program shall include administrative, technical, and physical safeguards to protect
47 against anticipated threats or hazards and unauthorized access to or theft of customer assets or
48 information.
49 (d) Incident Notification. – A financial institution shall notify the regulating authority of
50 any material cybersecurity incident as soon as possible, but in no event later than 72 hours after
51 discovering the incident. This notice shall provide a description of the incident and its likely
House Bill 1029-First Edition Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 impact on the financial institution and its customers, in accordance with any notification
2 procedures prescribed by the regulating authority. For purposes of this subsection, a "material
3 cybersecurity incident" means a cybersecurity breach or event that materially compromises the
4 security, confidentiality, or integrity of the financial institution's information systems or the
5 digital assets under its control.
6 (e) Record Keeping. – A financial institution shall maintain detailed records of its
7 compliance efforts under this section, including all policies, procedures, risk assessments, audit
8 reports, and training materials related to its anti-money laundering and cybersecurity programs.
9 All records and supporting documentation shall be retained for at least five years and shall be
10 made available for inspection by the regulating authority upon request or during an examination.
11 (f) Program Oversight Personnel. – A financial institution shall designate qualified
12 individuals responsible for overseeing the institution's anti-money laundering and cybersecurity
13 programs. The designated anti-money laundering compliance officer and the designated
14 cybersecurity program officer shall have the expertise, authority, and resources to administer
15 their respective programs and to enforce compliance with all applicable laws. A financial
16 institution shall promptly report to the Commissioner the names and contact information of these
17 designated individuals and shall notify the Commissioner of any change in these designations.
18 "§ 53-447. Prohibition on rehypothecation.
19 A financial institution shall not rehypothecate a customer's digital assets.
20 "§ 53-448. Unclaimed digital assets.
21 Digital assets held by a financial institution under this Article that are presumed abandoned
22 are subject to Article 4 of Chapter 116B of the General Statutes. For purposes of that Article, a
23 financial institution holding digital assets is a holder as defined in G.S. 116B-52, and the
24 customer is an apparent owner as defined in G.S. 116B-52.
25 "§ 53-449. Rulemaking.
26 The State Banking Commission and Credit Union Commission may adopt rules to
27 implement, clarify, and enforce the requirements of this Article. These rules may include more
28 specific standards for anti-money laundering, cybersecurity, and customer due diligence
29 programs. The State Banking Commission and Credit Union Commission may also issue
30 advisory guidance to assist financial institutions in complying with this Article.
31 "§ 53-450. Enforcement and supervisory authority.
32 (a) Grounds. – The regulating authority may exercise the enforcement powers set forth
33 in this section, if the regulating authority determines that a financial institution has done any of
34 the following:
35 (1) Violated any provision of this Article or rule adopted or order issued under it.
36 (2) Engaged in any unsafe or unsound practice in connection with its digital asset
37 services.
38 (3) Operated in a manner that threatens the safety or security of a customer's
39 digital assets.
40 (b) Corrective Action Orders. – The regulating authority may issue a written order
41 directing a financial institution to take specific corrective action to remedy any misconduct
42 described in subsection (a) of this section. The order shall state the grounds for issuance and the
43 required remedial measures. The financial institution shall, within 10 days of receiving the order,
44 respond in writing to the regulating authority detailing the corrective actions taken or planned.
45 (c) Temporary Emergency Orders. – If the regulating authority determines that a
46 financial institution has engaged in any misconduct described in subsection (a) of this section
47 and this misconduct is likely to cause immediate and irreparable harm to its customers or the
48 public, the regulating authority may issue a temporary emergency order. This order may direct
49 the financial institution to immediately cease and desist from the activity and take any other
50 action necessary to prevent or mitigate the harm. A temporary emergency order is effective upon
51 service on the financial institution. A financial institution subject to a temporary emergency order
Page 8 House Bill 1029-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 shall be given the opportunity for an expedited hearing. Upon the financial institution's request,
2 a hearing shall be held within 10 days after the issuance of the temporary emergency order to
3 determine whether the order should be stayed, modified, or made permanent. If no hearing is
4 requested within the 10-day period, or if the financial institution fails to appear at the scheduled
5 hearing, the temporary emergency order remains in effect until the regulating authority either
6 lifts it or replaces it with a cease and desist order under subsection (d) of this section.
7 (d) Cease and Desist Orders. – The regulating authority may, after notice and an
8 opportunity for hearing, issue an order requiring a financial institution to cease and desist from
9 any activity described in subsection (a) of this section. The regulating authority shall serve upon
10 the financial institution a written notice describing the alleged misconduct and specifying a time
11 and place for a hearing to be held within 15 days of the notice, at which the financial institution
12 may present evidence or argument. If the regulating authority finds that the financial institution
13 has engaged in the alleged misconduct, the regulating authority may issue a cease and desist order
14 ordering the financial institution to immediately discontinue the misconduct and take affirmative
15 action, if necessary, to prevent its recurrence.
16 (e) Suspension or Revocation of Digital Asset Service Authority. – If, after notice and an
17 opportunity for hearing, the regulating authority determines that a financial institution has
18 engaged in any misconduct described in subsection (a) of this section, the regulating authority
19 may suspend or revoke the institution's authority to provide digital asset services under this
20 Article. A notice of intent to suspend or revoke shall be served upon the financial institution,
21 stating the grounds for the action and setting a hearing at which the financial institution may
22 show cause why its authority should not be suspended or revoked. A suspension or revocation
23 issued under this subsection becomes effective only after the financial institution has been given
24 notice, an opportunity for a hearing, and a written decision by the regulating authority affirming
25 the grounds for the suspension or revocation.
26 (f) Civil Penalty. – In addition to or instead of an order described in this section, the
27 regulating authority may impose a civil penalty for any misconduct described in subsection (a)
28 of this section. For the first offense, the civil penalty shall not exceed five thousand dollars
29 ($5,000) per violation. For each subsequent offense, the penalty shall not exceed ten thousand
30 dollars ($10,000) per violation. Each act or omission that is found to constitute a violation is a
31 separate violation for purposes of assessing civil penalties. The regulating authority shall give
32 written notice to the financial institution of the proposed civil penalty, identifying the misconduct
33 and the amount of the penalty, and shall inform the financial institution of its right to request a
34 hearing on the civil penalty in accordance with subsection (g) of this section.
35 (g) Hearing and Appeal Rights. – A financial institution subject to an enforcement action
36 under this section is entitled to a hearing of the regulating authority's decision. Upon request by
37 the financial institution, the Commissioner shall conduct an administrative hearing within 15
38 days of the request. The financial institution may present evidence and argument at the hearing,
39 and the regulating authority shall issue a written final decision or order based on the record of
40 the proceeding. A bank may appeal a final decision or order of the Commissioner of Banks to
41 the State Banking Commission, in accordance with G.S. 53C-2-6, and a credit union may appeal
42 a final decision or order of the Administrator of Credit Unions to the Credit Union Commission,
43 in accordance with G.S. 54-109.92(k). The filing of an appeal operates as an automatic stay of
44 the regulating authority's order, unless the reviewing commission, upon motion of the regulating
45 authority, finds that a stay would pose a substantial risk to the public interest."
46 SECTION 1.(b) G.S. 116B-52 reads as rewritten:
47 "§ 116B-52. Definitions.
48 In this Chapter:The following definitions apply in this Chapter:
49 (1) "Apparent owner" means a person whose name appears on the records of a
50 holder as the person entitled to property held, issued, or owing by the holder.
